1) USD/TRY Exchange Rates from 01.2005 to 11.2020

As it can be seen below, the exchange rate of USD/TRY has followed these values, with concerning codes:

setwd("D:/Lectures/(2020-2021) Lectures Junior/IE360/Assignments/1")

library(ggplot2)
library(knitr)
library(markdown)

exc <- read.table(file="hw1_data1.txt", header=TRUE)

attach(exc)

usdplot <- ggplot(exc, aes(date, usd))

usdplot + geom_point(color="red") + geom_line() + 
          labs(title = "USD/TRY at Each Month From 01.2010 to 11.2020", x = "Date (in months)", y = "USD-TRY Exchange Rate",  
               caption = "https://evds2.tcmb.gov.tr/index.php?/evds/archiveMarket/collapse_0/5862/DataGroup/turkish/bie_dkdovizgn/")

# + geom_text(aes(label=months), angle = 90, size = 2, nudge_y = 0.2)
# + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

save.image("hw1_data1_R.RData")

ggsave("plot1.png", width = 80, height = 10, limitsize = FALSE)

Its shape is not changing at all at the beginning, 01.2010, and following months. Yet, sometimes USD/TRY value increases a little bit and continues its route with higher values, like step functions. Besides, in the last years its shape is changing so rapidly because of these reasons:

  1. Economical fluctuationsâ freqeuncies and their amplitudes due to domestic and foreign policies of the ruling party.
  2. Having a decreasing confidence level against Turkish economics concerning not only for consumers but also producers/investors.

When we look at the graph of the search volume of âdolarâ term taken from Google Trends, we can see the similarity. These two graphs simile each other in general, the general trend between them is alike. In short, when one of them increases at any time, the other is, too. Also, if we compare different halves of each graphs, it can be concluded that shapes of each graph is changing significcantly. At the first half of the first graph taken from TCMB database, we have stable exchange rate but at the second half of the graph, we have unstable exchange rate that changes a Also, year after year, its graph doesnât change significantly at the first time when the data are taken, but at the end the difference between years is much more. The same condition holds for the second graph, too. There is no similarity among each half each graph, i.e.Â distributions of each half is different than the other

Comparing both graphs related with the term âaltÄ±nâ, first graph taken from the TCMB database shows that the first half of the dataâs shape is not similar to the other. Even both of them are ragged, the first half has more rags than the second half. Moreover, second half has more stable increases and decreases. Also, when comparing each year with the former one for each graph, the new yearâs distribution is not similar to before, i.e.Â amounts change each year significantly; especially for some years, there are more than significant changes. For the Google Trendsâ graph, first half and the second half of the graph seems to have more stable increases and decreases except some years, but its distribution definitely changes at the second half.

3) Banksâ Total Amount of Dollars (in millions) from 01.2012 to 08.2020

The amounts of dollars in millions are given below according to TCMBâs data: 

setwd("D:/Lectures/(2020-2021) Lectures Junior/IE360/Assignments/1")

bankusd <- read.table(file="hw1_data3.txt", header=TRUE)

attach(bankusd)

library(ggplot2)
library(knitr)
library(markdown)

bankplot <- ggplot(bankusd, aes(number, amount))

bankplot + geom_point(color="purple") + geom_line(color = "black") + geom_step(color="red", alpha=0.3) +
  labs(title = "Banks' Total Amount of Dollars (in millions) From 01.2012 to 08.2020", x = "Date", y = "Dollars (in millions)",  
       caption = "https://evds2.tcmb.gov.tr/index.php?/evds/archiveMarket/collapse_0/5862/DataGroup/turkish/bie_dkdovizgn/") 

save.image("hw1_data3_R.RData")

From these graphs, it can be concluded that if each graph is halved and compared, TCMBâs graph shows more linear shape besides its second half, when its shape is again increasing same before but it is not as ragged as before. Yet, in the second half of the TCMBâs data, it can be observed that there is again increase but its increases make more great fluctuations. Also, if it is analyzed year after year, there is no similarity or stability, its values change every year.

When it comes to examine the Google Trendsâ data, there is no similarity between the first half and the second half of the graph. Also, each year has different search volume amount not related to the former one. At the beginning, its shape is less ragged, but at the second half, its increase has more stable shape but again have rags but deeper than before. At the end of the graph, its shape has the greatest peaks and pits. In other words, its distribution is different at each half.
